TYPE SCRIPT



In TypeScript, both interface and type are used to define shapes of objects, specifying the structure of data. While they share similarities, there are key differences between them:

interface:
Declaration:

Declares a named object type.
typescript
Copy code
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}
Extending:

Supports extending other interfaces.
typescript
Copy code
interface Employee extends Person {
  role: string;
}
Declaration Merging:

Automatically merges multiple declarations with the same name.
typescript
Copy code
interface Car {
  brand: string;
}

interface Car {
  model: string;
}

// Merged interface
// { brand: string, model: string }
Compatibility:

Interfaces can be used with the implements keyword for class implementation.
typescript
Copy code
class Student implements Person {
  // Must implement name and age properties
  name: string;
  age: number;
}
type:
Declaration:

Creates a named or anonymous object type.
typescript
Copy code
type Person = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
};
Extending:

Supports creating union, intersection, and mapped types.
typescript
Copy code
type Employee = Person & { role: string };
Declaration Merging:

Does not automatically merge multiple declarations with the same name. Instead, it produces an error.
typescript
Copy code
type Car = {
  brand: string;
};

type Car = {
  model: string;
};
// Error: Duplicate identifier 'Car'.
Compatibility:

Types are often used with union types for broader compatibility.
typescript
Copy code
type Student = {
  name: string;
} | {
  id: number;
};
When to Use Which:
Prefer interface when:

You need declaration merging.
You are working with instances of a class (implements).
You want to define objects with named types.
Prefer type when:

You need union, intersection, or mapped types.
You want to create reusable complex types.
You need to define anonymous types.

